ze:M mark:(line,black) width:25\n\n bar:period\n from: 1820    till: 1830    color:1800syears    text:[[1820s in paleontology|20s]]\n from: 1830    till: 1840    color:1800syears    text:[[1830s in paleontology|30s]]\n from: 1840    till: 1850    color:1800syears    text:[[1840s in paleontology|40s]]\n from: 1850    till: 1860    color:1800syears    text:[[1850s in paleontology|50s]]\n from: 1860    till: 1870    color:1800syears    text:[[1860s in paleontology|60s]]\n from: 1870    till: 1880    color:1800syears    text:[[1870s in paleontology|70s]]\n from: 1880    till: 1890    color:1800syears    text:[[1880s in paleontology|80s]]\n from: 1890    till: 1900    color:1800syears    text:[[1890s in paleontology|90s]]\n from: 1900    till: 1910    color:1900syears    text:[[1900s in paleontology|00s]]\n from: 1910    till: 1920    color:1900syears    text:[[1910s in paleontology|10s]]\n from: 1920    till: 1930    color:1900syears    text:[[1920s in paleontology|20s]]\n from: 1930    till: 1940    color:1900syears    text:[[1930s in paleontology|30s]]\n from: 1940    till: 1950    color:1900syears    text:[[1940s in paleontology|40s]]\n from: 1950    till: 1960    color:1900syears    text:[[1950s in paleontology|50s]]\n from: 1960    till: 1970    color:1900syears    text:[[1960s in paleontology|60s]]\n from: 1970    till: 1980    color:1900syears    text:[[1970s in paleontology|70s]]\n from: 1980    till: 1990    color:1900syears    text:[[1980s in paleontology|80s]]\n from: 1990    till: 2000    color:1900syears    text:[[1990s in paleontology|90s]]\n from: 2000    till: 2010    color:2000syears    text:[[2000s in paleontology|00s]]\n from: 2010    till: 2020    color:2000syears    text:[[2010s in paleontology|10s]]\n from: 2020    till: 2030    color:2000syears    text:[[2020s in paleontology|20s]]\n from: 2030    till: 2040    color:2000syears    text:[[2030s in paleontology|30s]]\n from: 2040    till: 2050    color:2000syears    text:[[2040s in paleontology|40s]]\n\n bar:era         \n from: 1820    till: 1900    color:1800s    text:[[19th century in paleontology|19th]]\n from: 1900    till: 2000    color:1900s    text:[[20th century in paleontology|20th]]\n from: 2000    till: 2050    color:2000s    text:[[21st century in paleontology|21st]]\n</timeline>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Spinosauridae Spinosauridae] on the Theropod Database\n{{Theropoda|T.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q131199}}\n{{Portal bar|Dinosaurs|Cretaceous}}\n\n[[Category:Spinosaurids| ]]\n[[Category:Kimmeridgian first appearances]]\n[[Category:Kimmeridgian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Tithonian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Berriasian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Valanginian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Hauterivian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Barremian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Aptian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Albian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Cenomanian taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Cenomanian extinctions]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Ernst Stromer]]\n", "name_user": "OviraptorFan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinosauridae"}
{"title_page": "San Rafael station", "text_new": "{{infobox station\n| name        = San Rafael\n| image       = \n| type        = [[Commuter rail]]\n| address     = [[Tlalnepantla de Baz|Tlalnepantla]], [[State of Mexico]]\n| country     = [[Mexico]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|19|33|55.2|N|99|11|43.4|W|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| owned       = [[Tren Suburbano|Ferrocarriles Suburbanos]]\n| operator    = Ferrocarriles Suburbanos\n| platforms   = 1 island platform\n| tracks      = 2\n| lines       =\n| opened      = {{Start date and age|2008|6|2|df=y}}\n| services    = {{Adjacent stations|system=Ferrocarril Suburbano|line=1|left=Tlalnepantla|right=Lecher\u00eda}}\n}}\n'''San Rafael''' is a station serving the [[Ferrocarril Suburbano]], a [[suburban rail]] that connects the [[State of Mexico]] with [[Mexico City]]. The station is located in the municipality of [[Tlalnepantla de Baz|Tlalnepantla]], State of Mexico, north of Mexico City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fsuburbanos.com/secciones/operacion/recorrido.php|title=Ferrocarriles Suburbanos - Estaciones|website=fsuburbanos.com|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==General information==\nSan Rafael station is located in the San Rafael industrial area in [[Tlalnepantla de Baz|Tlalnepantla]] and it is the fourth station of the system going northbound from [[Buenavista station]]. The station mainly services the factories area as well as inhabitants of the Tlayapa neighborhood.<ref name=eluniversal>{{cite news|title=San Rafael: la estaci\u00f3n que no pesca nada|url=https://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/ciudad/90296.html|newspaper=El Universal|first=Juan Manuel|last=Barrera|date=25 May 2008|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nAs with [[Mexico City Metro]], each station of the [[Ferrocarril Suburbano]] has a pictogram. San Rafael's pictogram depicts a fish. In many representations, [[Raphael (archangel)|Saint Raphael]] can be seen holding a fish, therefore, a fish was chosen as the station's pictogram.<ref>{{cite magazine|publisher=Ineco|date=December 2008|title=Cercan\u00edas en M\u00e9xico para cien millones de viajeros al a\u00f1o|url=http://www.ineco.es/clientes/itransporte/Minisite_Itransporte/Secciones/En%20Portada/en_portada_diciembre_08.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701134557/http://www.ineco.es/clientes/itransporte/Minisite_Itransporte/Secciones/En%20Portada/en_portada_diciembre_08.pdf|archive-date=1 July 2010|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nJardines del Recuerdo, one of [[Greater Mexico City]]'s most notable graveyards is located near the station.\n\n==History==\nSan Rafael station opened on 2 June 2008 as part of the first stretch of system 1 of the [[Ferrocarril Suburbano]], going from [[Buenavista Station]] in [[Mexico City]] to the Lecher\u00eda station in the [[State of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/tren-suburbano-inaugurated.html|title=Tren Suburbano inaugurated|journal=[[Railway Gazette International]]|date=1 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416204841/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/tren-suburbano-inaugurated.html|archive-date=16 April 2019|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore its construction, most of the area was a barren land, except for the nearby factories. Illegal housing could also be found in the zone. Once the construction of San Rafael station was announced and after the station was inaugurated, several housing projects were developed in the area.<ref>{{cite web|title=El elemento urbanizante: la creaci\u00f3n de la estaci\u00f3n San Rafael del tren suburbano y su efecto urbanizador|url=http://zaloamati.azc.uam.mx/handle/11191/2495|first=Manuel|last=de la Vega Orozco|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nDuring its first years of operation, San Rafael station reported very little ridership. In occasions, trains would stop at the station as it is customary, but would not open the doors, since there were no passengers at the station.<ref name=eluniversal/>\n\nIn 2009, between San Rafael and [[Lecher\u00eda station]], two trains crashed, with around 100 people injured.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los lamentables accidentes del Tren Suburbano|url=https://www.unionedomex.mx/articulo/2017/06/29/transporte/los-lamentables-accidentes-del-tren-suburbano|publisher=UN1\u00d3N Edomex|date=29 June 2017|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{| border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=400 valign=top|Exits/Entrances\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=3 valign=top|'''G<br>Platforms'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|Northbound\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=390|\u2190 [[File:Ferrocarril Suburbano.svg|16px]] [[File:FS1.png|16px]] toward [[Cuautitl\u00e1n station|Cuautitl\u00e1n]] {{small|([[Lecher\u00eda station|Lecher\u00eda]])}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Island platform]], doors will open on the left}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Southbound\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|{{0|\u2192}} [[File:Ferrocarril Suburbano.svg|16px]] [[File:FS1.png|16px]] toward [[Buenavista Station|Buenavista]] {{small|([[Tlalnepantla Station|Tlalnepantla]])}}\u2192\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ferrocarril Suburbano stations|San Rafael]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox station\n| name        = San Rafael\n| image       = \n| type        = [[Commuter rail]]\n| address     = [[Tlalnepantla de Baz|Tlalnepantla]], [[State of Mexico]]\n| country     = [[Mexico]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|19|33|55.2|N|99|11|43.4|W|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| owned       = [[Tren Suburbano|Ferrocarriles Suburbanos]]\n| operator    = Ferrocarriles Suburbanos\n| platforms   = 1 island platform\n| tracks      = 2\n| lines       =\n| opened      = {{Start date and age|2008|6|2|df=y}}\n| services    = {{Adjacent stations|system=Ferrocarril Suburbano|line=1|left=Tlalnepantla|right=Lecher\u00eda}}\n}}\n'''San Rafael''' is a station serving the [[Ferrocarril Suburbano]], a [[suburban rail]] that connects the [[State of Mexico]] with [[Mexico City]]. The station is located in the municipality of [[Tlalnepantla de Baz|Tlalnepantla]], State of Mexico, north of Mexico City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fsuburbanos.com/secciones/operacion/recorrido.php|title=Ferrocarriles Suburbanos - Estaciones|website=fsuburbanos.com|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==General information==\nSan Rafael station is located in the San Rafael industrial area in [[Tlalnepantla de Baz|Tlalnepantla]] and it is the fourth station of the system going northbound from [[Buenavista station]]. The station mainly services the factories area as well as inhabitants of the Tlayapa neighborhood.<ref name=eluniversal>{{cite news|title=San Rafael: la estaci\u00f3n que no pesca nada|url=https://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/ciudad/90296.html|newspaper=El Universal|first=Juan Manuel|last=Barrera|date=25 May 2008|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nAs with [[Mexico City Metro]], each station of the [[Ferrocarril Suburbano]] has a pictogram. San Rafael's pictogram depicts a fish. In many depictions, [[Raphael (archangel)|Saint Raphael]] can be seen holding a fish, therefore, a fish was chosen as the station's pictogram.<ref>{{cite magazine|publisher=Ineco|date=December 2008|title=Cercan\u00edas en M\u00e9xico para cien millones de viajeros al a\u00f1o|url=http://www.ineco.es/clientes/itransporte/Minisite_Itransporte/Secciones/En%20Portada/en_portada_diciembre_08.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701134557/http://www.ineco.es/clientes/itransporte/Minisite_Itransporte/Secciones/En%20Portada/en_portada_diciembre_08.pdf|archive-date=1 July 2010|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nJardines del Recuerdo, one of [[Greater Mexico City]]'s most notable graveyards is located near the station.\n\n==History==\nSan Rafael station opened on 2 June 2008 as part of the first stretch of system 1 of the [[Ferrocarril Suburbano]], going from [[Buenavista Station]] in [[Mexico City]] to the Lecher\u00eda station in the [[State of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/tren-suburbano-inaugurated.html|title=Tren Suburbano inaugurated|journal=[[Railway Gazette International]]|date=1 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416204841/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/tren-suburbano-inaugurated.html|archive-date=16 April 2019|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore its construction, most of the area was a barren land, except for the nearby factories. Illegal housing could also be found in the zone. Once the construction of San Rafael station was announced and after the station was inaugurated, several housing projects were developed in the area.<ref>{{cite web|title=El elemento urbanizante: la creaci\u00f3n de la estaci\u00f3n San Rafael del tren suburbano y su efecto urbanizador|url=http://zaloamati.azc.uam.mx/handle/11191/2495|first=Manuel|last=de la Vega Orozco|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nDuring its first years of operation, San Rafael station reported very little ridership. In occasions, trains would stop at the station as it is customary, but would not open the doors, since there were no passengers at the station.<ref name=eluniversal/>\n\nIn 2009, between San Rafael and [[Lecher\u00eda station]], two trains crashed, with around 100 people injured.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los lamentables accidentes del Tren Suburbano|url=https://www.unionedomex.mx/articulo/2017/06/29/transporte/los-lamentables-accidentes-del-tren-suburbano|publisher=UN1\u00d3N Edomex|date=29 June 2017|access-date=1 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{| border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=400 valign=top|Exits/Entrances\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=3 valign=top|'''G<br>Platforms'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|Northbound\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=390|\u2190 [[File:Ferrocarril Suburbano.svg|16px]] [[File:FS1.png|16px]] toward [[Cuautitl\u00e1n station|Cuautitl\u00e1n]] {{small|([[Lecher\u00eda station|Lecher\u00eda]])}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Island platform]], doors will open on the left}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Southbound\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|{{0|\u2192}} [[File:Ferrocarril Suburbano.svg|16px]] [[File:FS1.png|16px]] toward [[Buenavista Station|Buenavista]] {{small|([[Tlalnepantla Station|Tlalnepantla]])}}\u2192\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ferrocarril Suburbano stations|San Rafael]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Cocu15", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeneral information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Rafael_station"}
{"title_page": "Maxine Peake", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Maxine Peake\n| image                 = MaxinePeak 2015.JPG\n| caption               = Peake in February 2015\n| imagesize             = \n| birthname             = \n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1974|07|14}} \n| birth_place           = [[Westhoughton]], [[Greater Manchester]], England\n| death_date            =  <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|1974|07|14}} Death date then birth -->\n| death_place           = \n| occupation            = Actress\n| years_active          = 1996\u2013present\n| spouse                = \n}}\n\n'''Maxine Peake''' (born 14 July 1974) is an English actress. She is best known for her roles as Twinkle in ''[[Dinnerladies (TV series)|Dinnerladies]]'' and [[List of Shameless (British TV series) characters#Veronica Ball|Veronica Ball]] in ''[[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]'', barrister Martha Costello in the BBC legal drama ''[[Silk (TV series)|Silk]]'',<ref name=BBC-Silk>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/13/bbc1-silk-maxine-peake |title=Maxine Peake to star in BBC1 legal drama Silk |first=Jason |last=Deans |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 July 2010 |accessdate=4 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529155303/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/13/bbc1-silk-maxine-peake |archivedate=29 May 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Grace Middleton in the BBC drama series ''[[The Village (2013 TV series)|The Village]]'', as well as starring in ''Black Mirror'' episode \"[[Metalhead (Black Mirror)|Metalhead]]\". She is also an accomplished stage actress, having played the title role in ''[[Hamlet]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nPeake was born in [[Westhoughton]], Bolton<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=p4%2F%2FDzfGtKNV6L2l%2FHr7Vw&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=14 January 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> on 14 July 1974,<ref name=\"Independent-2008-03\">{{cite news |first=Charlotte |last=Philby |title=My Secret Life: Maxine Peake, actress, 33 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=8 March 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/my-secret-life-maxine-peake-actress33-791121.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420233213/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/my-secret-life-maxine-peake-actress33-791121.html |archivedate=20 April 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the second of two daughters born to Glenys (''n\u00e9e'' Hall) and Brian Peake.<ref name=\"Mail091107\">{{cite news |first=Maureen |last=Paton |title=Maxine Peake: From rugby league to starring actress |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=9 November 2007 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-492708/Maxine-Peake-From-rugby-league-starring-actress.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130420052302/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-492708/Maxine-Peake-From-rugby-league-starring-actress.html |archivedate=20 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Her father was a lorry driver before working in the electrical industry, and her mother was a part-time careworker. Her older sister, Lisa (born 1965), is a police officer.<ref name=\"Mail091107\"/> Peake's parents separated when she was nine and she lived with her mother until the age of 15. When her mother moved in with a new boyfriend several miles away, Peake went to live with her grandfather so she could continue her [[GCSE]] studies at Westhoughton High School, before going on to take her [[A-Levels]] at [[Canon Slade School]] in [[Bradshaw, Greater Manchester|Bradshaw]]. Her grandfather encouraged her to develop her creativity and start acting.\n\nPeake joined the [[Octagon Theatre, Bolton|Octagon Youth Theatre]] in [[Bolton]] at age 13, before a period at the youth theatre of the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester|Royal Exchange]] in Manchester. She later did a two-year performing arts course at the [[Salford College of Technology]].<ref name=\"Guardian-2010-05\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/may/15/maxine-peake-interview|title=Maxine Peake: The Misfit|last=Mitchison|first=Amanda|date=15 May 2010|work=The Guardian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607003008/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/may/15/maxine-peake-interview|archivedate=7 June 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=4 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During this time she appeared in productions with two leading amateur theatre companies in Bolton: The Marco Players and The Phoenix Theatre Company. Peake was a member of the [[Communist Party of Britain]] Salford branch in her youth.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://lancashire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/maxine-peake--my-lovely-lancashire-home-38257 |title=Maxine Peake \u2013 My lovely Lancashire home |work=Lancashire Life |date=4 January 2012 |accessdate=13 October 2012 |quote=When I was much younger I used to be a member of the Communist Party although nowadays I don't really have a political affiliation to any party.}}</ref> In her teens, Peake played for Wigan Ladies [[rugby league]] team.<ref>{{cite news |title=From running on rugby league fields to acting on the Hollywood big screen |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/league/from-running-on-rugby-league-fields-to-acting-on-the-hollywood-big-screen/story-e6frf3ou-1226780413830 |accessdate=11 December 2013 |publisher=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |date=11 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nPeake's early attempts to enter the acting profession were unsuccessful. She was rejected by every theatre education company in [[North West England]],<ref name=\"Guardian-2009-10\">{{cite news |first=Amy |last=Raphael |title=Justice at last for Maxine Peake |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 October 2009 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2009/oct/03/maxine-peake-criminal-justice |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310024810/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2009/oct/03/maxine-peake-criminal-justice |archivedate=10 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and tried unsuccessfully for three years to get into [[Manchester School of Theatre|Manchester Polytechnic Theatre School]] and the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]].<ref name=\"Mail091107\" /> However, at 21, she obtained a place at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA). Her attempts to find sponsorship for RADA were the subject of a 1996 documentary by ''[[The South Bank Show]]''. Eventually, after being put forward by RADA, she was awarded the [[Patricia Harmsworth, Viscountess Rothermere|Patricia Rothermere]] Scholarship.<ref name=Guardian-2010-05 /><ref name=Independent-2006-06>{{cite news |first=Alice |last=Jones |title=Maxine Peake: Onward and upward |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=22 June 2006 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/maxine-peake-onward-and-upward-405028.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603212551/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/maxine-peake-onward-and-upward-405028.html |archivedate=3 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Hayfestival-2016-brotton-essiedu-peake.jpg|thumb|right|Peake (right) with [[Jerry Brotton]] and [[Paapa Essiedu]] at the 2016 [[Hay Festival]]]]\nPeake has appeared in a number of television and stage productions including [[Victoria Wood]]'s ''[[dinnerladies]]'', [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]'', in the lead role of barrister Martha Costello in the BBC's legal drama ''[[Silk (TV series)|Silk]]'' and alongside [[John Simm]] in the BBC drama ''[[The Village (2013 TV series)|The Village]]'', depicting life in a [[Derbyshire]] village during the [[First World War]].<ref>[http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/the-village.pdf \"''The Village'' Press Pack\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402051707/http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/the-village.pdf |date=2 April 2013 }}, BBC Press Office, 19 March 2013. Retrieved 19 March 2013.</ref> Following career advice from [[Victoria Wood]], between the two series of ''dinnerladies'', Peake lost so much weight that an explanation had to be written into the script for her character, Twinkle.<ref name=Guardian-2010-05 />\n\nPeake portrayed the [[Moors murders|Moors murderer]] [[Myra Hindley]] in ''[[See No Evil: The Moors Murders]]''.<ref name=\"MEN040506\">[http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/film_and_tv/s/212/212234_return_to_the_moors.html \"Return to the Moors\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070416064048/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/film_and_tv/s/212/212234_return_to_the_moors.html |date=16 April 2007 }} ''[[Manchester Evening News]]'', 4 May 2006</ref> Broadcast in May 2006, it was met with mixed reactions; soon after this Peake announced that she was leaving ''Shameless''. January 2009 saw Peake appear in her first major feature film role, as Angela, in the film ''[[Clubbed]]''.\n\nShe has played the title role in ''[[Miss Julie]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester|Royal Exchange]], Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalexchangecasting.co.uk/missjulie.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014143931/http://www.royalexchangecasting.co.uk/missjulie.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 October 2014|title=''Miss Julie'' Cast List|publisher=Royal Exchange Theatre|accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref> She previously played the part of Kristin in a 2000 production.<ref>[http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0151072196/Eccleston+Woos+Miss+Julie+at+Haymarket.html \"Eccleston Woos Miss Julie at Haymarket\"]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''What's on Stage'', 19 January 2000. Retrieved 5 March 2012.</ref> as well as [[Doll Tearsheet]] in the BBC2 adaptations of ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Parts I and II]]''.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Cast confirmed for BBC Two's cycle of Shakespeare films |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/shakespeare-cast.html |publisher=BBC Drama Publicity |date=24 November 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64JKhsWGc?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/shakespeare-cast.html |archivedate=30 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, a play that Peake had written, directed and starred in about the life of the [[Leeds]]-born cyclist [[Beryl Burton]] was broadcast on [[BBC Radio Four]] as ''Beryl: A Love Story On Two Wheels''.<ref name=\"cyclingweekly\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/bbc-to-broadcast-beryl-burton-radio-drama-36703 |title=BBC to broadcast Beryl Burton radio drama |first=Richard |last=Abraham |work=[[Cycling Weekly]] |date=20 November 2012 |accessdate=4 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607001541/http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/bbc-to-broadcast-beryl-burton-radio-drama-36703 |archivedate=7 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2012/48/r4-wk48-beryl.html|title=Beryl: A Love Story On Two Wheels|publisher=BBC|accessdate=20 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925074300/http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2012/48/r4-wk48-beryl.html|archivedate=25 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2014 Peake adapted her play for the stage.  Titled simply ''Beryl'', it was commissioned by the West Yorkshire Playhouse where it ran in June and July 2014 to coincide with the start of the [[2014 Tour de France|Tour de France]] in Leeds,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-27923596|title=Maxine Peake celebrates unsung sporting hero Beryl Burton|date=24 June 2014|accessdate=20 July 2015|author=Ian Youngs|work=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925164609/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-27923596|archivedate=25 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> returned in June and July 2015 and toured across England in Autumn 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wyp.org.uk/latest_news/beryl-on-tour|title=Tour de Beryl|publisher=West Yorkshire Playhouse|date=8 July 2015|accessdate=20 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004181156/https://www.wyp.org.uk/latest_news/beryl-on-tour/|archivedate=4 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Peake wrote a later play called ''Queens of the Coal Age'' again for Radio 4 that told the story of [[Annie Scargill]] and three other women who tried to occupy a coal mine during the [[UK miners' strike (1984\u201385)|1980s Miners' Strike]].<ref name=queens>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03g937t Queens of the Coal Age] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221162233/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03g937t |date=21 December 2016 }}, BBC. Retrieved 29 April 2017</ref>\n\nPeake provided the vocals for the Eccentronic Research Council's 2012 concept album ''1612 Underture'' about the [[Pendle witches|Pendle Witch Trials]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/09784-the-eccentronic-research-council-and-maxine-peake |work=The Quietus |title=The Eccentronic Research Council And Maxine Peake |first=John |last=Doran |date=22 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130204120230/http://thequietus.com/articles/09784-the-eccentronic-research-council-and-maxine-peake |archivedate=4 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and for their 2015 album ''Johnny Rocket, Narcissist & Music Machine\u2026I'm Your Biggest Fan''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/17950-the-eccentronic-research-council-johnny-rocket-narcissist-music-machine-im-your-biggest-fan-review |work=The Quietus |title=The Eccentronic Research Council \u2013 Johnny Rocket, Narcissist & Music Machine... I'm Your Biggest Fan |first=Tristan |last=Bath |date=27 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20160421070834/http://thequietus.com/articles/17950-the-eccentronic-research-council-johnny-rocket-narcissist-music-machine-im-your-biggest-fan-review |archivedate=21 April 2016 |df=dmy-all |access-date=13 April 2017 }}</ref> Peake also features as a crazed stalker in the music video for \"Sweet Saturn Mine\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweet Saturn Mine|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-f_yV3N2e8|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003095201/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-f_yV3N2e8|archivedate=3 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> by Moonlandingz; a collaborative effort by Eccentronic Research Council and Fat White Family in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maxine Peake Stalks the Fat Whites...|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/feb/14/maxine-peake-fat-white-family-moonlandingz|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416000550/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/feb/14/maxine-peake-fat-white-family-moonlandingz|archivedate=16 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Peake was appointed an Associate Artist of the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester|Royal Exchange]] Theatre in Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet The Creative Team|url=http://www.royalexchange.co.uk/meet-the-company|publisher=Royal Exchange Theatre|accessdate=9 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419005432/http://www.royalexchange.co.uk/meet-the-company|archivedate=19 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Her association with the theatre began in childhood and she was a member of the youth theatre. Major productions in which she has performed include ''[[The Children's Hour (play)|The Children's Hour]]'' in 2008, for which she won a [[Manchester Evening News Theatre Awards|MEN Award]], and ''[[Miss Julie]]'' in 2012 for which she won a [[Manchester Theatre Awards|Manchester Theatre Award]]. All of her performances at the Royal Exchange have been directed by [[Sarah Frankcom]] with whom she also collaborated on ''[[The Masque of Anarchy]]'' in 2012 for the [[Manchester International Festival]]. Building on this work, in September 2014 Frankcom went on to direct her as the title character in a radical re-imagining of ''[[Hamlet]]''.<ref name=\"Royal Exchange Press Release\">{{cite web|url=http://www.royalexchange.co.uk/news_detail.aspx?article=500|title=Royal Exchange Press Release|publisher=royalexchange.co.uk|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> The demand for tickets was so great that the production was extended for a week, having been \"the theatre's fastest-selling show in a decade\".<ref>\"Maxine Peake's run as Hamlet at Royal Exchange extended by a week\", ''Manchester Evening News'', 1 September 2014.</ref> ''The Guardian'' said of her performance: \"Peake\u2019s delicate ferocity, her particular mixture of concentration and lightness, ensure that you want to follow her whenever she appears\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Hamlet Review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/sep/21/hamlet-maxine-peake-royal-exchange-review-delicate-ferocity|work=The Guardian|accessdate=8 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408084003/http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/sep/21/hamlet-maxine-peake-royal-exchange-review-delicate-ferocity|archivedate=8 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A year later she appeared in Frankcom's production of ''The Skriker'', as \"Caryl Churchill's shape-shifting, doom-wreaking fairy\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Skriker review \u2013 extraordinarily prescient|url = https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/jul/12/skriker-review-extaordinarily-prescient-caryl-churchill-maxine-peake|website = The Guardian|accessdate = 23 December 2015|first = Susannah|last = Clapp|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151223144740/http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/jul/12/skriker-review-extaordinarily-prescient-caryl-churchill-maxine-peake|archivedate = 23 December 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> ''The Guardian''<nowiki/>'s Lyn Gardner listed the production in her top ten British plays of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lyn Gardner's top 10 theatre of 2015|url = https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/dec/17/lyn-gardner-top-10-theatre-of-2015|website = The Guardian|accessdate = 23 December 2015|first = Lyn|last = Gardner|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151223012100/http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/dec/17/lyn-gardner-top-10-theatre-of-2015|archivedate = 23 December 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> In 2016, Peake resumed her partnership with Royal Exchange Artistic Director, Sarah Frankcom, to star as Blanche Dubois in Tennessee Williams' ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire]]''. Peake's performance in the role garnered critical acclaim with The Guardian describing her performance as \"exquisite\" and \"breathtaking.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/sep/14/a-streetcar-named-desire-review-a-superb-and-tragic-spectacle-michael-billington|title=A Streetcar Named Desire review \u2013 Maxine Peake is a breathtaking Blanche|last=Billington|first=Michael|date=2016-09-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 it was announced that Peake was to star in [[Mike Leigh]]'s next feature, ''[[Peterloo (film)|Peterloo]]'', a feature film based on the events of the [[Peterloo Massacre|1819 Peterloo Massacre]] in Manchester.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/maxine-peake-joins-mike-leighs-peterloo-1018670|title=Maxine Peake Joins Mike Leigh's 'Peterloo' (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2017-08-27|language=en}}</ref> In August 2017 it was revealed that Peake was to star in an episode of Netflix's ''[[Black Mirror]]''. The episode entitled, \"[[Metalhead (Black Mirror)|Metalhead]]\", was directed by ''[[Hannibal (TV series)|Hannibal]]'' and ''[[American Gods (TV series)|American Gods]]'' director, [[David Slade]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/black-mirror-season-4-cast-episodes-trailer-netflix-1202156121/|title=\u2018Black Mirror\u2019: Season 4 Cast & Episode Info, Teaser Trailer Released By Netflix|last=Haring|first=Bruce|date=2017-08-25|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-08-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nPeake starred as the eponymous protagonist in the 2018 film [[Funny Cow]] alongside a cast including [[Paddy Considine]] and [[Stephen Graham]]. The film was written by and also starred [[Tony Pitts]] and received positive reviews, in particular praising Peake's \"magnificent\" performance.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/22/funny-cow-review-maxine-peake-paddy-considine</ref>\n\nPeake starred in, and won critical acclaim for, the lead role of Winnie in [[Samuel Beckett]]'s [[Happy Days (play)|Happy Days]] at the [[Royal Exchange Theatre]] in May 2018, with The Guardian calling hers a \"brilliant central performance, there\u2019s barely a breath between optimism and despair.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/may/31/happy-days-review-maxine-peake-winnie-climate-chaos-beckett|title=Happy Days review \u2013 Maxine Peake is transfixed by climate chaos|last=Love|first=Catherine|date=2018-05-31|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref> Following Happy Days, the theatre presented ''Queens of the Coal Age'', a play written by Peake. Adapted from her earlier radio drama,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03g937t|title=Queens of the Coal Age, Afternoon Drama - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref> ''Queens of the Coal'' age looks at the early 1990s pit closure protests by miners' wives in northern England. The play was met with mixed reviews.<ref name=\"The Stage\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2018/queens-coal-age-review-maxine-peake-royal-exchange-theatre-manchester/|title=Queens of the Coal Age review at Royal Exchange Theatre, Manchester|work=The Stage|access-date=2018-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"The Stage\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jul/05/queens-of-the-coal-age-review-maxine-peake-shines-light-on-womens-fight-for-the-mines|title=Queens of the Coal Age review \u2013 Maxine Peake shines light on women's fight for the mines|last=Love|first=Catherine|date=2018-07-05|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref>\n\nPeake is set to star in ''The Nico Project'' as [[The Velvet Underground|Velvet Underground]] singer Nico at the [[Manchester International Festival]] in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/maxine-peake-nico-play-velvet-underground-manchester-international-festival-a8813621.html|title=Maxine Peake to star as Nico in play about the singer's 'dark side'|date=2019-03-08|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2009, Peake left London after living there for 13 years. The move freed her of the financial constraints of trying to buy a house in the area. Living in [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]] with her art director partner Pawlo Wintoniuk, she says, gave her the freedom to choose more risky roles and lower-paying jobs in theatre. \"For the last few years I have been lucky enough to choose what I want to do. Living in Salford gives me the confidence to do that because I don't have a massive mortgage.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Maxine Peake on Leaving London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/11458832/Maxine-Peake-on-leaving-London-being-old-fashioned-and-playing-Hamlet.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=7 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404094230/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/11458832/Maxine-Peake-on-leaving-London-being-old-fashioned-and-playing-Hamlet.html|archivedate=4 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2014, she said that in an attempt to have children she had explored every option, including [[IVF|IVF treatments]], and has suffered two miscarriages.<ref>{{cite web|title=It's So Selfish to Have Children|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2742885/It-s-selfish-children-claims-Silk-star-Maxine-Peake-Actress-questions-people-s-motivation-starting-family.html|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=7 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150407191601/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2742885/It-s-selfish-children-claims-Silk-star-Maxine-Peake-Actress-questions-people-s-motivation-starting-family.html|archivedate=7 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\n[[File:Jeremy Corbyn and Maxine Peake, Tolpuddle 2016.jpg|thumb|Jeremy Corbyn and Maxine Peake walking together in the procession through the village at the [[Tolpuddle Martyrs' Festival and Rally]] 2016]]\nPeake brings her views into much of her work.<ref>Ed Cumming, [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/jan/17/maxine-peake-interview-red-top-socialism Maxine Peake: \u2018I care deeply what people think\u2019] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214000239/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/jan/17/maxine-peake-interview-red-top-socialism |date=14 December 2016 }}, ''The Guardian'', 17 January 2016.</ref> She is a [[feminism|feminist]] and socialist. She was active in [[communism|communist]] organisations during her youth and a member of [[Communist Party of Britain]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/17/maxine-peake-hope-corbyn-people-power-peterloo-radical-legacy</ref> In January 2014, Peake won the first Bolton Socialist Club Outstanding Contribution to Socialism Award, for using her work to oppose the government's \"crippling austerity measures\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Saiqa |last=Chaudhari |url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/10928497.Maxine_Peake_wins_socialism_award_for_opposing_austerity_measures/ |title=Maxine Peake wins socialism award for opposing austerity measures |publisher=[[The Bolton News]] |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=4 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320084313/http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/10928497.Maxine_Peake_wins_socialism_award_for_opposing_austerity_measures/ |archivedate=20 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Peake endorsed [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s [[2015 Jeremy Corbyn Labour Party leadership campaign|campaign]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour Party leadership election]]. She wrote on her website: \"For me, Jeremy Corbyn is our only beacon of hope to get the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] back on track, get the electorate back in touch with politics and save this country from the constant mindless bullying of the vulnerable and poor.\"<ref name=\"morningstaronline\">{{cite news|last=James|first=Luke|url=http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/a-45b8-Peake-Corbyn-can-put-Labour-on-track|title=Peake: Corbyn can put Labour on track|publisher=[[Morning Star (British newspaper)|Morning Star]]|date=11 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150809233504/http://morningstaronline.co.uk/a-45b8-Peake-Corbyn-can-put-Labour-on-track|archivedate=9 August 2015|df=dmy-all|access-date=7 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Peake featured in the [[The Climate Coalition (UK)|Climate Coalition]]'s short film ''I Wish For You'' as Mia, with [[Jeremy Irons]] starring as her grandfather, to highlight the urgency on combating [[climate change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.bt.com/entertainment/i-wish-for-you-91364038273689|title=Maxine Peake stars in new climate change film 'I Wish for You...'|publisher=BT.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407095452/http://home.bt.com/entertainment/i-wish-for-you-91364038273689|archivedate=7 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, along with numerous other celebrities, Peake toured the UK to support Jeremy Corbyn's bid to become [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].<ref name=\"jc4pmtour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jc4pmtour.com/|title=#JC4PM|work=|location=|publisher=jc4pmtour|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=15 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701133711/http://jc4pmtour.com/|archive-date=1 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|last=Wilkinson|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/12134051/Celebrities-to-tour-Britain-in-Jeremy-Corbyn-For-Prime-Minister-musical-show.html|title=Celebrities to tour Britain in 'Jeremy Corbyn For Prime Minister' musical show|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=15 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609221909/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/12134051/Celebrities-to-tour-Britain-in-Jeremy-Corbyn-For-Prime-Minister-musical-show.html|archivedate=9 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Peake endorsed Labour Party leader Jeremy Corbyn in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]]. She said: \"I am a Corbyn supporter. My mind boggles why people treat him like the [[Antichrist|anti-Christ]], but it goes to show people are a lot more right-wing than they like to believe.\"<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news|last=Hattenstone|first=Simon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/apr/29/maxine-peake-corbyn-supporter-need-coup|title=Maxine Peake: 'I'm a Corbyn supporter. We need a coup'|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 April 2017|accessdate=14 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606140616/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/apr/29/maxine-peake-corbyn-supporter-need-coup|archivedate=6 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, along with other public figures, Peake signed a letter supporting Labour Party leader Jeremy Corbyn describing him as \"a beacon of hope in the struggle against emergent far-right nationalism, xenophobia and racism in much of the democratic world\" and endorsed him in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 UK general election]].<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite news |last=Neale|first=Matthew|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/new-letter-supporting-jeremy-corbyn-2568734|title=Exclusive: New letter supporting Jeremy Corbyn signed by Roger Waters, Robert Del Naja and more |work=[[NME]]|location= |date=16 November 2019|accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Girls' Night]]''\n|Sharon\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2002\n|''[[All or Nothing (film)|All or Nothing]]''\n|Party Girl\n|\n|-\n|''Hamilton Mattress''\n|Lulu\n|Short; voice role\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" |2005\n|''Be Mine''\n|Tina's Mum\n|Short\n|-\n|''[[Frozen (2005 film)|Frozen]]''\n|Ticket Attendant\n|\n|-\n|''Stealing Up''\n|Daughter\n|Short\n|-\n|2006\n|''The Madness of the Dance''\n|The Professor\n|Short\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2007\n|''I Am Bob''\n|Marilyn Monroe\n|Short\n|-\n|''Would Like to Meet''\n|Heather\n|Short\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Clubbed]]''\n|Angela\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2010\n|''Alice''\n|\n|Short\n|-\n|''Edge''\n|Elly\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2011\n|''[[Room at the Top (2012 film)|Room at the Top]]''\n|Alice Aisgill\n|\n|-\n|''[[Best Laid Plans (2012 film)|Best Laid Plans]]''\n|Isabel\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Private Peaceful (film)|Private Peaceful]]''\n|Hazel Peaceful\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n|''[[Run & Jump]]''\n|Vanetia Casey\n|\n|-\n|''[[Svengali (2013 film)|Svengali]]''\n|Angie\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" |2014\n|''[[The Falling (2014 film)|The Falling]]''\n|Eileen\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Theory of Everything (2014 film)|The Theory of Everything]]''\n|Elaine Mason\n|\n|-\n|''Keeping Rosy''\n|Charlotte\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|''[[Dispossession: The Great Social Housing Swindle]]''\n| Narrator\n| Docum